      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne ¶ 29/1/74. ¶  ¶ Just returned from an exploring trip to the snowy mountains, rev. and dear Sir, I find your kind letter of the 15. inst. ¶ Letter not found. ¶  ¶ I had the pleasure of corres...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">74.01.29</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Branwhite Clarke</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">ML MSS.3608 Clarke papers, Mitchell Library, State Library of New South Wales, Sydney.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; "/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>For a published version of this letter, see Moyal (2003), pp. 1006-7.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>Melbourne</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">29/1/74.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Just returned from an exploring trip to the snowy mountains, rev. and dear Sir, I find your kind letter of the 15. inst.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I had the pleasure of corresponding with Mr James, who <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(so I understand) is gone again to Sydney, and became acquainted with his excellent son, spending several days with him on the Hume River.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        </seg>It is uncertain what current name, if any, represents the stream M calls 'Hume River'.<space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Charles Sturt's name 'Murray River' of 1830, not the earlier name 'Hume River' given by William Hovell<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>to honour his companion Hamilton Hume who first saw it in their 1824-5 journey, is the one that appears on official maps from at least Thomas Mitchell's 1838 map<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(digitized as<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <ref target="https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-230586259">
                           <seg rend="Hyperlink" style="color: #0000FF; ">https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-230586259</seg>
                        </ref>).</p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>'Hume River' appears on labels of specimens collected on this trip, for example<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Centaurium pulchellum</seg>, MEL 709285, and on others from the region collected by M correspondents, for example Sydney Jephcott<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(see<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>O. Norstedt to M, 20 May 1889 (in this edition as 89-05-20a)). Jephcott's specimen of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Coronidium scorpiodes</seg>, MEL 2115511,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>has the locality 'Hume River', but the catalogue locality entry is <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'Hume River [=Upper Murray River]';<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>see also George (2007), p. 431. However, in M to<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>G.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Bentham, 27 January 1874,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>M discriminated between three rivers: 'For Brasenia peltata I have now three new localities, the Hume-River, Mitta Mitta &amp; Upper Murray River',<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>making the location doubtful. In that letter,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>M<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>implies that the Hume is a border between NSW and Vic: 'On the N.S. Wales side of the Hume-river I found…'.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Wright (1898), in discussing the nomenclature of the Murray River, wrote 'The upper waters of the river are known, in New South Wales only, as the Hume' (pp. 35-6). However, no contemporary use of the name has been found in gazetteers or maps of NSW, although throughout the 1880s and 1890s,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>NSW<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>government gazette notices routinely used the phrase 'Murray or Hume River' in describing boundaries anywhere in the whole course of the river.</p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It appears that M was using the term to refer to part of the waterway, perhaps what was described as 'the Indi or Hume River, the principal source of the Murray',<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in 'Interesting Geological Discovery',<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Australian town and country journal</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(Sydney), 19 February 1870, p. 16). See the 1872 map of Victoria<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <ref target="https://catalogue.nla.gov.au/catalog/587540">
                           <seg rend="Hyperlink" style="color: #0000FF; ">https://c</seg>
                           <seg rend="Hyperlink" style="color: #0000FF; ">a</seg>
                           <seg rend="Hyperlink" style="color: #0000FF; ">talogue.nla.gov.au/catalog/587540</seg>
                        </ref>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in which the first part of the stream from the source where the river meets the Black-Allan Line, surveyed in 1870-72 from Cape Howe to the nearest source of the Murray is labelled 'Indi', and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>that<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>downstream from<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>around<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Tom Groggin<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>to the vicinity of Towong<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is a section labelled 'Indi or Murray River', with the remaining portion labelled 'Murray River'.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am very sorry, that I missed Major Clarke,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>W. B. Clarke’s son, Mordaunt Clarke. See also M to W.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>B.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Clarke, 25 April 1874.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>but I enquired at four leading Hotels (including Scotts) but could hear nothing of his abode. I will send to morrow to the Military Office, and should I learn that he is still here, I will do myself the honor of waiting on him.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have read your adresses<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>W. B.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Clarke (1873),<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>W. B.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Clarke<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(1874).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>with great interest; they reflect, like all you do, much honor on your genius &amp; unabating assiduity. I wonder,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>whether through Major Warburton's Expedition or that of Giles<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Expeditions by P. Warburton and E. Giles, westwards from the Overland Telegraph Line.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>we shall at last learn, what became of poor Leichhardt's party.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I met lately Mr Nicholson's family, whose brother<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mark Nicholson, brother of Leichhardt’s close friend<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>William Nicholson, had settled in Victoria.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>was so generous to Leichhardt.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When you meet Mrs Cobham,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mary Cobham?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>— pray — give her my best regards.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Amidst the arrear work of the Department (if such in its helpless state it still can be called) I have but a few moments left to bid you a most cordial "adieu"</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Always your regardful</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
